******
[2]Cordoba Province (Ticino)
Date: Thu, 10 May 2012
Source: La Voz [Translated from Spanish by MPP, edited]
http://www.lavoz.com.ar/ciudadanos/confirmaron-tres-casos-triquinosis-ticino


Three cases of trichinosis confirmed in Ticino.
------------------
Those affected are already in good health. The disease cam from the consumption of fresh sausages or salami.

Three people from Ticino, near Villa Maria and 206 kms southeast of Cordoba were confirmed to have trichinosis. This was announceby by the deputy director of the Pasteur de Villa Maria Hospital, Ignacio Bruno, who added that the 3 patients are under outpatient treatment (at home) and are in good health after having been hospitalized for a few days.

According to the statement by the Hospital physician, the 3 affected individuals had eaten pork products locally that had not been kept in cold storage". The provincial Ministry of Health also issued an official statement about these cases mentioning that the municipality would implement hygienic and sanitary measure to avoid a larger outbreak.

Last week, when they had the 1st indications of an outbreak, the mayer of Ticino, Renato Lorenzatti, announced to the press that recommendations had been made to pork vendors that precautions were needed.

The Ministry of Health of Cordoba, through the Department of Epidemiology confirmed the outbreak in Ticino and issued an alert on the dangers of eating pork products of dubious origin and without a corresponding health inspection. According to investigations, at the moment, the only common link established was the consumption of salami or fresh sausages acquired in the same locality.

The investigation and pertinent control measures are being conducted jointly by professionals from the Department of Epidemiology of the Ministry of Health, the Food And Drug Control Secretariat of the Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock and Food, and SENASA with collaboration with the Municipality of Ticino.

